<div id="outline-container-1-2-1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-1-2-1"><span class="section-number-4">1.2.1</span> proc</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-1-2-1">

<dl>
<dt>Questions</dt><dd>
<ol>
<li>What's the CPU type and model? <code>/proc/cpuinfo</code>
<pre class="example">
less /proc/cpuinfo
model name   : AMD Athlon(tm) II Dual-Core M320
</pre>

</li>
<li>What version of the Linux kernel are you using? <code>uname -srv</code>



<pre class="example">uname -srv
Linux 3.4.7-1.fc16.i686.PAE
</pre>

</li>
<li>How long has it been since your PC last booted? <code>uptime</code>
<pre class="example">
uptime
10 min
</pre>

</li>
<li>How much of the total CPU time has been spent executing in user mode? kernel mode? idle? <code>top</code>
<pre class="example">
top
Cpu(s): 33.3%us, 14.4%sy,  0.0%ni, 49.5%id,  0.5%wa,  1.9%hi,  0.5%si,  0.0%st
</pre>

</li>
<li>How much memory is configured in your PC? <code>top,free,/proc/meminfo</code>
<pre class="example">
top
Mem:   2065512k total,  1323912k used,   741600k free,    35252k buffers
</pre>




<pre class="example">free
total       used       free     shared    buffers     cached
Mem:       2065512    1328644     736868          0      35276     491808

less /proc/meminfo
MemTotal:        2065512 kB
MemFree:          694840 kB
</pre>

</li>
<li>How much memory is currently available? <code>top,free,/proc/meminfo</code>
<pre class="example">
top
741600k free
</pre>

</li>
<li>How many disk read/write requests have been made? <code>/proc/diskstats</code>
<pre class="example">
cat /proc/diskstats
21919
</pre>

</li>
<li>How many context switches has the kernel performed? <code>/proc/stat</code>
<pre class="example">
cat /proc/stat
1057275779
</pre>

</li>
<li>How many context switches has a process had? <code>/proc/[pid]/status</code>
<pre class="example">
cat /proc/status
voluntary_ctxt_switches:     1432
nonvoluntary_ctxt_switches:  685
</pre>

</li>
<li>How many processes have been created since the system was booted? <code>/proc/stat</code>
<pre class="example">
cat /proc/stat
processes 15865
</pre>

</li>
<li>How many processes are there in the ready queue? <code>/proc/stat</code>
<pre class="example">
cat /proc/stat
procs_running 2
</pre>

</li>
<li>How many processes are blocked waiting for I/O to complete? <code>/proc/stat</code>
<pre class="example">
cat /proc/stat
procs_blocked 0
</pre>

</li>
<li>What does the following command do?



<pre class="example">cd /proc/`ps | head -2 | tail -1 | cut -f2 -d' '` &amp;&amp; ls -l
</pre>

<pre class="example">
ls -l `the directory of bash PID=4872`
equals to ls -l /proc/4872/
</pre>

</li>
</ol>

</dd>
</dl>


</div>

</div>

<div id="outline-container-1-2-2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-1-2-2"><span class="section-number-4">1.2.2</span> Play with the Kernel</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-1-2-2">

<dl>
<dt>Tasks</dt><dd>
<ol>
<li>Find the following "famous" code, and tell me why they are "famous".
<ul>
<li>start_kernel();
</li>
<li><a href="http://cs3.swfc.edu.cn/linux-source/HTML/S/12025.html#L134">find me here</a>



<pre class="example">the system start with start_kernel(),it's just like
main function at c and it finished most of the kernel
initial things.
</pre>

</li>
<li>init();
</li>
<li><a href="http://cs3.swfc.edu.cn/linux-source/HTML/S/12025.html#L134">find me here</a>
</li>
<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_startup_process">more details form wiki</a>



<pre class="example">init (short for initialization) is a program for Unix-based
computer operating systems that spawns all other processes.
It runs as a daemon and typically has PID 1. The boot loader
starts the kernel and the kernel starts init. If one were to
delete init without a replacement, the system would encounter
a kernel panic on the next reboot.
</pre>

</li>
<li>struck task_struck;
</li>
<li><a href="http://linuxgazette.net/133/saha.html">find me here</a>



<pre class="example">it manage the processes of a system     
</pre>

<dl>
<dt>The following shows the linked list representation of processes in memory</dt><dd>
</dd>
</dl>

<p>           <img src="http://linuxgazette.net/133/misc/saha/l-list.png"  alt="http://linuxgazette.net/133/misc/saha/l-list.png" />
</p></li>
<li>struct inode;
</li>
<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inode">more details from the wiki</a>



<pre class="example">In computing, an inode (index node) is a data structure found
in many Unix file systems. Each inode stores all the information
about a file system object (file, directory, device node, socket,
pipe, etc.), except data content and file name.[1]
</pre>

</li>
<li>struct file;
</li>
<li><a href="http://cs3.swfc.edu.cn/linux-source/HTML/S/4419.html#L576">find me here</a>



<pre class="example">a file structure delegates a opened file,each opened file in the
system are related to a struct file,it's created by kernel when
open a file,and send to the function to operate the file,when
closed the file,then system released it.
</pre>

</li>
<li>fork(); <code>man 2 fork</code>



<pre class="example">fork - create a child process
</pre>

</li>
<li>include/asm-generic/unistd.h <code>man unistd</code>



<pre class="example">DESCRIPTION
The  &lt;unistd.h&gt;  header  defines  miscellaneous  symbolic constants and
types, and declares miscellaneous functions. The actual values  of  the
constants  are unspecified except as shown. The contents of this header
are shown below.
</pre>

</li>
<li>arch/x86_64/entry.S
</li>
<li><a href="http://www.lingcc.com/2011/12/05/11872/">find it here</a>



<pre class="example">as you can see it's a assembly file with .S,
this file defined x86 platform's Terminal vector array.
it's archived by the assembler so that the programmer can
control the assembly file more flexible.
</pre>

</li>
<li>kernel/printk.c
</li>
<li><a href="http://baike.baidu.com/view/3201386.htm">refer to&hellip;</a>



<pre class="example">the printk is just like printf in c Programming,but there
is a different between them,printk works in kernel;printf
works in user-mode.because the function tty_write(to write result in tty)
needs string,which is pointed by fs,only the printf can use fs.
printk should make fs point to the ds(data segment register).
in a word,the fs makes them different.
</pre>

</li>
</ul>

</li>
<li>Finish lesson 2-6 of LinuxChix Kernel Hacking Lessons (cs2 mirror). And you are encouraged to go through lesson 7-9 as well, though it's not mandatory.
</li>
</ol>

</dd>
</dl>


